2026-04-21 01:34:42 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module timing potentiometer'] hypothesis_explanation='All measurements show that the 12 V supply from the power module is stable and that the control module’s relay contacts continuously deliver ~11.8 V to the load, even when the lamp briefly turns off every ~20 s. The relay is seen closed and does not chatter; the input and output of the control module do not drop. \n\nIn the load module, the protection diode anode and cathode both sit near 12 V while the lamp flicker occurs, and the main and indicator lamps have stable, correct resistances with no intermittency under mechanical stress, ruling out filament or socket faults. Inter‑module cabling likewise shows a stable voltage during flicker, excluding connector opens.\n\nThe only subsystem repeatedly implicated by the simulator as ‘unstable or oscillating’ is the timing network around the ambient sensor module timing potentiometer. When the timing pot was driven toward its minimum‑time end, the simulator explicitly reported non‑convergence/oscillation, and subsequent voltage checks show its wiper effectively disconnected or at an undefined potential (11.85 V on one end, ~0 V on the other, wiper not properly participating). This suggests an internal fault in the timing potentiometer (e.g., open wiper/contact or damaged resistive track) that causes the control circuit’s threshold node to oscillate on a roughly 20 s time constant, momentarily driving the relay circuitry into an unstable state that translates, through the oscillating control electronics, into a brief interruption of current through the lamp despite the relay contacts appearing closed on DC measurement.\n\nBecause all other components (battery, LEDs, lamps, diode, cabling, relay contacts) have been effectively cleared by measurements, the most plausible and specific root cause is a defective timing potentiometer in the ambient sensor module. Replacing this potentiometer (and re‑calibrating the timing) is expected to eliminate the ~20 s, 0.5 s lamp outages.'
